1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,640
So, let's start right away with a pretty tough question.

2
00:00:03,640 --> 00:00:08,040
Can faith in God or religious authority in general end up hindering

3
00:00:08,040 --> 00:00:09,560
the development of democracy?

4
00:00:09,560 --> 00:00:11,759
It almost sounds like a provocation, doesn't it?

5
00:00:11,759 --> 00:00:17,839
Well, a very peculiar historical research gives us an answer that is quite surprising.

6
00:00:17,839 --> 00:00:20,920
And to understand it, we have to solve an enigma.

7
00:00:20,920 --> 00:00:25,440
And pay attention, we're not talking about a simple far-fetched theory.

8
00:00:25,480 --> 00:00:29,000
This is the conclusion of a very serious academic study

9
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:33,280
that has put together a huge amount of data to bring to light

10
00:00:33,280 --> 00:00:36,560
a historical dynamic that remained hidden for centuries.

11
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:37,560
So, where are we?

12
00:00:37,560 --> 00:00:38,480
Northern Italy.

13
00:00:38,480 --> 00:00:42,120
And when? In a period of great, very great turmoil,

14
00:00:42,120 --> 00:00:44,640
between the year one thousand and thirteen hundred.

15
00:00:44,640 --> 00:00:48,159
The cities that until then were dominated by feudal lords,

16
00:00:48,159 --> 00:00:49,799
start to rebel.

17
00:00:49,799 --> 00:00:52,680
It's the beginning of the so-called communal movement,

18
00:00:52,680 --> 00:00:55,240
a very powerful push towards self-government

19
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:58,039
that will forever change the face not only of Italy,

20
00:00:58,039 --> 00:00:59,520
but of all of Europe.

21
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:01,719
But to solve our mystery,

22
00:01:01,719 --> 00:01:04,120
there is one fundamental detail to understand.

23
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:06,240
Not all cities were the same.

24
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:07,240
In fact.

25
00:01:07,240 --> 00:01:10,120
In that period, two completely different

26
00:01:10,120 --> 00:01:12,439
models of power existed.

27
00:01:12,439 --> 00:01:15,920
But first, let's clarify: what exactly was a commune?

28
00:01:15,920 --> 00:01:18,560
Look, it wasn't just a simple change at the top.

29
00:01:18,560 --> 00:01:21,520
No, it was a real revolution.

30
00:01:21,520 --> 00:01:24,120
Power passed from the hands of a single lord

31
00:01:24,120 --> 00:01:26,520
to those of the citizens' representatives,

32
00:01:26,520 --> 00:01:29,040
complete with constitutions and assemblies.

33
00:01:29,040 --> 00:01:31,640
For the first time, merchants, artisans,

34
00:01:31,640 --> 00:01:34,520
in short, common people had a say.

35
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:38,400
They could decide on taxes, laws, their own city.

36
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:40,159
And here we are at the crucial point.

37
00:01:40,159 --> 00:01:43,360
On one side, there were cities with secular lords.

38
00:01:43,360 --> 00:01:46,840
Where politics and religion were two separate things.

39
00:01:46,840 --> 00:01:49,960
On the other hand, episcopal cities.

40
00:01:49,960 --> 00:01:52,680
And here the bishop was not only the spiritual head,

41
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:54,520
but was also the political ruler.

42
00:01:54,520 --> 00:01:56,800
He held both powers in his hands.

43
00:01:56,800 --> 00:01:59,240
Now, let's keep this distinction in mind,

44
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:00,800
because it's the key to everything.

45
00:02:00,800 --> 00:02:04,920
And in this scenario already full of political and social changes,

46
00:02:04,920 --> 00:02:08,000
something totally unpredictable happens,

47
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,280
something terrifying.

48
00:02:10,280 --> 00:02:12,960
An event that doesn't just shake the earth,

49
00:02:12,960 --> 00:02:15,600
but the very foundations of power.

50
00:02:15,600 --> 00:02:18,480
Let's try to immerse ourselves in the medieval mindset.

51
00:02:18,480 --> 00:02:20,840
There was no science of plate tectonics,

52
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:23,680
the Richter scale didn't even remotely exist.

53
00:02:23,680 --> 00:02:25,640
An earthquake was only one thing:

54
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:28,920
the irrefutable proof of the Wrath of God,

55
00:02:28,920 --> 00:02:31,719
a divine punishment for the sins of the community.

56
00:02:31,719 --> 00:02:35,199
The panic was absolute, and there was only one question.

57
00:02:35,199 --> 00:02:37,319
How do we appease the Heavens?

58
00:02:37,319 --> 00:02:40,560
And mind you, this is not a modern interpretation.

59
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:45,319
Listen to what Filastrius, a bishop of Brescia, said as far back as the fourth century.

60
00:02:45,319 --> 00:02:48,400
To doubt that an earthquake was a divine act

61
00:02:48,439 --> 00:02:50,080
was considered heresy.

62
00:02:50,080 --> 00:02:54,480
The church itself, therefore, reinforced this belief with all its authority.

63
00:02:54,480 --> 00:02:57,800
And here our modern researchers come into play,

64
00:02:57,800 --> 00:03:00,439
real historical detectives.

65
00:03:00,439 --> 00:03:02,159
Armed not with magnifying glasses,

66
00:03:02,159 --> 00:03:04,240
but with databases and statistical models,

67
00:03:04,240 --> 00:03:06,759
they gathered information on centuries of history,

68
00:03:06,759 --> 00:03:10,080
they related the political regimes of every single city

69
00:03:10,080 --> 00:03:12,400
with every seismic event ever recorded,

70
00:03:12,400 --> 00:03:14,000
a crazy job.

71
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,080
Just to get an idea of the scale of this research,

72
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:20,920
we are talking about 121 cities in Northern Italy,

73
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:24,000
analyzed over a span of 300 years,

74
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:26,720
a simply enormous analysis.

75
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:28,720
Well, the investigation is concluded,

76
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:30,400
the evidence has been gathered,

77
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:32,080
and now hold on tight,

78
00:03:32,080 --> 00:03:34,200
because what the data revealed

79
00:03:34,200 --> 00:03:38,640
is as counter-intuitive as it is, I must say, fascinating.

80
00:03:38,640 --> 00:03:42,600
The researchers started, as is proper, with the control group.

81
00:03:42,600 --> 00:03:44,680
They took the non-episcopal cities,

82
00:03:44,680 --> 00:03:46,320
those with a secular ruler,

83
00:03:46,359 --> 00:03:50,280
and asked themselves, what happened here when the earth shook?

84
00:03:50,280 --> 00:03:54,680
Did the earthquake have any impact on their transition towards the commune?

85
00:03:54,680 --> 00:03:56,319
And the result was very clear.

86
00:03:56,319 --> 00:03:58,479
In the cities governed by a count,

87
00:03:58,479 --> 00:04:00,120
by a marquis, an earthquake

88
00:04:00,120 --> 00:04:01,680
changed absolutely nothing.

89
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:04,439
The process towards self-government, towards the commune,

90
00:04:04,439 --> 00:04:08,159
went on its way with or without seismic shocks.

91
00:04:08,159 --> 00:04:12,000
And now let's move to the heart of our mystery.

92
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:15,319
What happened instead in the episcopal cities?

93
00:04:15,439 --> 00:04:18,199
Those where religious power and political power

94
00:04:18,199 --> 00:04:20,560
were fused in the same person.

95
00:04:20,560 --> 00:04:24,599
And here is the discovery, the real revelation.

96
00:04:24,599 --> 00:04:26,519
In the cities governed by a bishop,

97
00:04:26,519 --> 00:04:29,360
an earthquake drastically reduced the probability

98
00:04:29,360 --> 00:04:30,879
of a commune being born.

99
00:04:30,879 --> 00:04:33,879
The movement towards self-government was blocked.

100
00:04:33,879 --> 00:04:35,560
Effectively blocked;

101
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:39,159
fear in practice ended up strengthening the existing power.

102
00:04:39,159 --> 00:04:41,800
OK, now we know what happened,

103
00:04:41,800 --> 00:04:44,959
but the most important question is still there waiting for us.

104
00:04:45,079 --> 00:04:47,560
Why? What was the exact mechanism

105
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:51,239
that linked a tremor of the earth to a block of democracy?

106
00:04:51,239 --> 00:04:54,759
The answer, as you may have guessed,

107
00:04:54,759 --> 00:04:56,599
lies precisely in that fusion,

108
00:04:56,599 --> 00:04:59,639
in that overlap between spiritual power

109
00:04:59,639 --> 00:05:03,639
and temporal power that characterized these specific cities.

110
00:05:03,639 --> 00:05:06,959
Let's retrace the chain of events together; it's very logical.

111
00:05:06,959 --> 00:05:09,599
First, the shock arrives: the earthquake.

112
00:05:09,599 --> 00:05:11,759
Second, people are terrified,

113
00:05:11,759 --> 00:05:14,279
they interpret it as divine punishment.

114
00:05:14,320 --> 00:05:17,720
Third, who do you turn to to appease an angry god?

115
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:21,560
Well, the only possible intermediary: the bishop.

116
00:05:21,560 --> 00:05:24,360
Fourth, consequently, the authority of the bishop—

117
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:26,360
both religious and political—

118
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:28,560
emerges enormously strengthened.

119
00:05:28,560 --> 00:05:29,560
And at that point,

120
00:05:29,560 --> 00:05:31,960
who would have ever dared to challenge a leader so invigorated

121
00:05:31,960 --> 00:05:34,880
by popular fear to create a new form of government?

122
00:05:34,880 --> 00:05:36,880
The status quo had won.

123
00:05:36,880 --> 00:05:38,120
But it's not over;

124
00:05:38,120 --> 00:05:42,240
the researchers found evidence that is almost a smoking gun,

125
00:05:42,240 --> 00:05:46,519
they analyzed data on the construction of new religious buildings

126
00:05:46,519 --> 00:05:48,280
like churches and cathedrals.

127
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:50,439
And the data, look, speak for themselves.

128
00:05:50,439 --> 00:05:54,319
In secular cities, after an earthquake, nothing special happens.

129
00:05:54,319 --> 00:05:55,840
But in the episcopal ones,

130
00:05:55,840 --> 00:06:00,199
there is a real boom in the construction of new churches.

131
00:06:00,199 --> 00:06:03,199
It is the proof that bishops knew how to capitalize on fear

132
00:06:03,199 --> 00:06:05,160
to consolidate their influence,

133
00:06:05,160 --> 00:06:07,720
their power, even materially.

134
00:06:07,720 --> 00:06:09,920
Certainly, it is a fascinating story.

135
00:06:09,920 --> 00:06:11,800
But what does it tell us today?

136
00:06:11,800 --> 00:06:14,079
Almost a thousand years later.

137
00:06:14,079 --> 00:06:18,240
What lesson can we draw from this episode so distant in time?

138
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:20,480
It teaches us something eternal, I would say:

139
00:06:20,480 --> 00:06:24,639
a crisis, whether it's an earthquake, a pandemic, or an economic crisis,

140
00:06:24,639 --> 00:06:26,759
is never just an objective fact.

141
00:06:26,759 --> 00:06:29,040
The way it is interpreted,

142
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:32,879
through the lens of our fears and our deepest beliefs,

143
00:06:32,879 --> 00:06:34,920
can change the course of history;

144
00:06:34,920 --> 00:06:38,639
it can strengthen existing power or, conversely, weaken it.

145
00:06:38,680 --> 00:06:42,399
And this brings us to a final question to reflect on.

146
00:06:42,399 --> 00:06:44,959
How much of our political debate today

147
00:06:44,959 --> 00:06:48,759
is still shaped not so much by logic or facts,

148
00:06:48,759 --> 00:07:00,120
but by fears and deep-seated beliefs,

149
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:54,759
whether they are religious, ideological, or otherwise.

150
00:06:54,759 --> 00:06:57,800
Perhaps, when the earth shakes under our feet,

151
00:06:57,800 --> 00:07:00,120
in a literal or metaphorical sense,

152
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:03,319
the Middle Ages are not as far away as we think.